In some ways, the quality of research may have suffered from the pressure to publish and increase turnover. Already at 2004 separate surveys reported that all faculty at the universities in Vienna (APO UCLA) and Graz (UPO AMA) were satisfied with their jobs and researchers were less satisfied with scientific developments.

Implicit in these results is the concern whether or not a purer research university would find at least partly different answers in this survey, necessarily more specialized ones.

Nevertheless, these results by and large are in keeping with earlier ones, and hence may be used as an initial pool on which to base comparisons. In due course it will be possible to compare these with younger groups under the umbrella of the strategy of benchmarking the later workforce.

Given, again, that there may be different patterns in the various branches of knowledge, it would be highly beneficial to somehow compare such results with the results of the research university.

Related to this, it is important to stress that while there are good examples with groups of senior staff embracing principles of lifelong learning as defined above and spontaneously doing everything possible to attract and guide younger researchers, training and further training is still not universal in Christiania. Compare, instead, the results of the different surveys on rising staff turnover in history, communications, physics and humanities where half the respondents felt that stability was an important factor for enjoyment at work and satisfaction with the university.
